  "text": "Kubernetes implements RBAC privilege escalation prevention through a multi-layered validation system. The core mechanism is in pkg/registry/rbac/escalation_check.go, which provides three key functions: EscalationAllowed() checks if a user is in the system:masters group (superuser), RoleEscalationAuthorized() checks if a user has explicit 'escalate' verb permission on role/clusterrole resources, and BindingAuthorized() checks if a user has 'bind' permission on specific role references.\n\nWhen users attempt to create or update ClusterRole, ClusterRoleBinding, Role, or RoleBinding resources, the policybased storage implementations in pkg/registry/rbac/{clusterrole,clusterrolebinding,role,rolebinding}/policybased/storage.go intercept these operations. In their Create() and Update() methods, they first check if escalation is allowed via EscalationAllowed() or RoleEscalationAuthorized(). If not allowed, they invoke ConfirmNoEscalationInternal() (for roles) or ConfirmNoEscalation() (for bindings).\n\nThe validation chain uses AuthorizationRuleResolver from pkg/registry/rbac/validation/rule.go to retrieve the current user's rules via RulesFor(), then employs the Covers() function from staging/src/k8s.io/component-helpers/auth/rbac/validation/policy_comparator.go to verify that the user's existing permissions completely cover (encompass) the permissions they're attempting to grant. If there's any permission mismatch, a Forbidden error is returned.\n\nThe helper functions in pkg/apis/rbac/helpers.go and pkg/apis/rbac/v1/evaluation_helpers.go provide utilities for parsing PolicyRules and matching verbs/resources, while plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/rbac.go implements the core RuleAllows() function that matches incoming requests against rules. The policy_compact.go module optimizes the error messages by consolidating simple rules before reporting missing permissions.\n\nThis architecture ensures that users can only escalate their own permissions (either by being a superuser, having explicit 'escalate' permission, or 'bind' permission), or by ensuring they already possess all the permissions they're attempting to delegate to others."
}

